@node Reload
@section Reload

@findex elpaca-extras-reload
After making local edits to an installed package or after a manual rebuild, the old feature definitions remain active in the running Emacs session. The command @code{elpaca-extras-reload} unloads and reloads the features provided by a specified package.

It works by scanning the package's installation directory for @samp{.el} files, extracting the feature names from their @code{provide} forms, forcefully unloading those features, and then requiring them again. By default, only features that were already loaded are reloaded. With a prefix argument, all features provided by the package are loaded regardless of their previous state.

@strong{Important:} because @code{unload-feature} is called with the @code{force} flag, any data stored in the package's symbols will be lost. If the package saves state on deactivation or Emacs exit, you should trigger that save before reloading.

@node Update and reload
@section Update and reload

@findex elpaca-extras-update-and-reload
The command @code{elpaca-extras-update-and-reload} combines updating a package via Elpaca with an automatic reload. It prompts for a queued package, triggers @code{elpaca-update}, and installs a temporary hook on @code{elpaca-post-queue-hook} to detect when the build finishes. If the build succeeds, it calls @code{elpaca-extras-reload} (@ref{Reload}) and reports the result. If the build fails, it directs you to the @samp{*elpaca-log*} buffer for details.

This provides a convenient single-step workflow: update, build, unload old definitions, and load the new ones.

@node Rebuild and reload
@section Rebuild and reload

@findex elpaca-extras-rebuild-and-reload
The command @code{elpaca-extras-rebuild-and-reload} is analogous to @code{elpaca-extras-update-and-reload} (@ref{Update and reload}) but uses @code{elpaca-rebuild} instead of @code{elpaca-update}. This is useful when you have made local source changes and want to rebuild the package from those changes rather than fetching upstream updates.

@node Lock file management
@section Lock file management

@findex elpaca-extras-write-lock-file-excluding
The command @code{elpaca-extras-write-lock-file-excluding} writes an Elpaca lock file to the specified PATH while filtering out packages listed in @code{elpaca-extras-write-lock-file-excluded} (@ref{@code{elpaca-extras-write-lock-file-excluded}, , User options}). When called interactively, it prompts for the output file path.

The optional ELPACAS argument accepts a queue-like list as used by @code{elpaca-write-lock-file}. When nil, the current queue is used. This makes it possible to call the function programmatically with a custom package set.

